ce:section.ce:para:
A facile one-pot hydrothermal method (Fig. 1
                        A) was adhibited to synthesize CDs using a variety of hydrazide derivatives (Fig. S1) as the precursor. To screen the CDs with the best anti-bacterial performance, the MIC values of these CDs were measured on four representative bacterial strains, including Gram-positive bacteria S. aureus, Gram-negative bacteria E. coli, and two kinds of drug-resistant bacteria MRSA and ESBL-E. Compared with other synthetic CDs, carbohydrazide-based CDs (CDH–CDs) showed the lowest MIC of 25 or 50 μg/mL (Table 1
                        ), suggesting the superior anti-bacterial activity of CDH–CDs over other hydrazide derivative-based CDs. Consequently, CDH–CDs were selected to make a profound study of their anti-bacterial performance.

Bacterial infection is an important reason that leads to the progression of chronic wounds, which significantly hinders wound healing [67]. Considering the excellent in vitro anti-bacterial activity of CDH–CDs, we developed experimental models by inducing artificial wounds infected with MRSA on the backs of the mice to appraise the in vivo anti-bacterial performance of CDH–CDs. One day after the mice models were created, the wounds were treated with PBS (control), the developed CDs CDH–CDs, or the precursor CDH by dropping, respectively (Fig. 6
                        A). Representative images and statistical analysis of the wound areas at different time points were illustrated in Fig. 6B-D. Excitingly, CDH–CDs treatment visibly expedited the wound healing progress compared to the wound treated with PBS or CDH. After 9 days of treatment, the relative wound area of the mice in the CDH–CDs treated group decreased to 14.2 %, which was conspicuously smaller than the PBS- (23.9 %) and CDH-treated group (36.0 %). At the end of the treatments, the mice were euthanized and the infected wounds were collected for H&E staining and Masson’s trichrome staining. As shown in Fig. 6E, minor inflammation, along with collagen deposition and follicle reoccurrence were observed in the stained slices of the wounds treated with CDH–CDs, while PBS- or CDH-treated wounds showed considerable inflammatory cell infiltration. These results depicted the potent anti-bacterial activity of CDH–CDs against bacterial infections. Subsequently, we evaluated the biocompatibility of CDH–CDs. In vitro cytotoxicity of CDH–CDs on the L929 mouse fibroblast cell line was first evaluated through MTT assay. As shown in Fig. S9, about 78.6 % of L929 cells survived when incubated with 50.00 μg/mL CDH–CDs for 48 h, suggesting CDH–CDs were slightly cytotoxic to L929 cells. Nevertheless, CDH–CDs retained potential for in vivo anti-bacterial applications through localized dropwise administration. In vivo toxicity studies further confirmed this conclusion. As demonstrated in Fig. S10, during the treatment regimen, the body weights of the mice in each group exhibited little discernible change. Simultaneously, histological examination of major organs (Fig. 7
                        ) and blood routine examination (Fig. S11) from the mice that received different treatments exhibited no obvious abnormalities compared to those of the healthy mice, demonstrating low systemic toxicity of CDH–CDs. Hemolysis tests of CDH–CDs also showed that, at a concentration up to 400 μg/mL, minimal hemolytic activity was reconnoitered (Fig. S12), indicating the good hemocompatibility of CDH–CDs. Taken together, our results demonstrated the excellent in vivo anti-bacterial performance of the developed CDs.
